#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:143
#, no-wrap
msgid "Systemd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:146
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Systemd* is a service manager for the Linux operating systems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:148
msgid "It is developed to:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:151
msgid "remain compatible with older SysV initialization scripts,"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:151
msgid ""
"provide many features, such as parallel start of system services at system "
"startup, on-demand activation of daemons, support for snapshots, or "
"management of dependencies between services."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:155
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Systemd is the default initialization system since RedHat/CentOS 7.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:157
msgid "Systemd introduces the concept of systemd units."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:163
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| Type         | File extension | Observation                              |\n"
"|--------------|----------------|------------------------------------------|\n"
"| Service unit | `.service`       | System service                           |\n"
"| Target unit  | `.target`        | A group of systemd units                 |\n"
"| Mount unit   | `.automount`     | An automatic mount point for file system |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:167
#, no-wrap
msgid "    There are many types of units: Device unit, Mount unit, Path unit, Scope unit, Slice unit, Snapshot unit, Socket unit, Swap unit, Timer unit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:169
msgid "Systemd supports system state snapshots and restore."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:171
msgid "Mount points can be configured as systemd targets."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:173
msgid ""
"At startup, systemd creates listening sockets for all system services that "
"support this type of activation and passes these sockets to these services "
"as soon as they are started. This makes it possible to restart a service "
"without losing a single message sent to it by the network during its "
"unavailability. The corresponding socket remains accessible and all messages "
"are queued."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:175
msgid ""
"System services that use D-BUS for their inter-process communications can be "
"started on demand the first time they are used by a client."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:177
msgid ""
"Systemd stops or restarts only running services. Previous versions (before "
"RHEL7) attempted to stop services directly without checking their current "
"status."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:179
msgid ""
"System services do not inherit any context (like HOME and PATH environment "
"variables). Each service operates in its own execution context."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:181
msgid ""
"All service unit operations are subject to a default timeout of 5 minutes to "
"prevent a malfunctioning service from freezing the system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:182
#, no-wrap
msgid "Managing system services"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:185
msgid ""
"Service units end with the `.service` file extension and have a similar "
"purpose to init scripts. The `systemctl` command is used to `display`, "
"`start`, `stop`, `restart` a system service:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:195
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| systemctl                                 | Description                             |\n"
"|-------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|\n"
"| systemctl start _name_.service            | Start a service                         |\n"
"| systemctl stop _name_.service             | Stops a service                         |\n"
"| systemctl restart _name_.service          | Restart a service                       |\n"
"| systemctl reload _name_.service           | Reload a configuration                  |\n"
"| systemctl status _name_.service           | Checks if a service is running          |\n"
"| systemctl try-restart _name_.service      | Restart a service only if it is running |\n"
"| systemctl list-units --type service --all | Display the status of all services      |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:197
msgid ""
"The `systemctl` command is also used for the `enable` or `disable` of system "
"a service and displaying associated services:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:205
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"| systemctl                                | Description                                             |\n"
"|------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|\n"
"| systemctl enable _name_.service            | Activate a service                                      |\n"
"| systemctl disable _name_.service           | Disable a service                                       |\n"
"| systemctl list-unit-files --type service | Lists all services and checks if they are running       |\n"
"| systemctl list-dependencies --after      | Lists the services that start before the specified unit |\n"
"| systemctl list-dependencies --before     | Lists the services that start after the specified unit  |\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/admin_guide/10-boot.md:207
msgid "Examples:"
msgstr ""

